A Strategic Decision
Don't make Sprint, Meetings, Daily Updates, Reviews, Documents, and Tasks independent top-level modules.
Instead, make them project capabilities that are always contextual.
For example:
A meeting belongs to a project and often to a sprint.
A sprint contains features, deliverables, and daily updates.
A feature contains its requirements, designs, code links, checklists, reviews, and approvals.
A module contains many features.
A roadmap contains many modules.
In other words, model KPM as a hierarchy of connected engineering objects rather than a collection of pages. That approach will make navigation feel natural, preserve context everywhere in the application, and allow powerful traceability—for example, being able to click from a roadmap milestone all the way down to the meeting where a design decision was made or the pull request that implemented it. I believe that object-oriented structure is what will distinguish KPM from conventional project management tools.

